[1]
Date: Wed 10 Feb 2010
Source: Queensland Health, media statement [edited]
<http://www.health.qld.gov.au/news/media_releases/measlesairlie_0210.pdf>


Measles case in Airlie Beach prompts QH alert
---------------------------------------------
Queensland Health (QH) is warning Whitsundays residents and recent
visitors to the area to be on the look out for the symptoms of
measles after a case of the infectious disease was confirmed in an
Airlie Beach tourist.

Tropical Regional Services medical officer Dr Steven Donohue said a
male tourist had the highly-contagious disease while visiting the
Whitsundays from 30 Jan to 4 Feb 2010.

"Although the patient didn't get measles in Australia, he would have
been highly infectious while in the Airlie Beach region," Dr Donohue
said. "We're concerned about the possibility of the measles virus
spreading into the local community and elsewhere in Queensland due to
the large number of travellers and visitors to the area.

"The patient took part in a range of activities in and around Airlie
Beach, and public health officers have been identifying those who may
have been exposed so appropriate advice can be given. Queensland
Health will continue to actively investigate all cases and take steps
to prevent further transmission."

Measles is extremely contagious and is spread in tiny droplets
through coughing and spluttering. The virus can last for several
hours in the environment. Measles can be very distressing for those
affected, and complications can include pneumonia and encephalitis
(inflammation of the brain). It can be a severe illness even in
otherwise healthy adolescents and young adults.

The initial symptoms are: fever, lethargy, runny nose, moist cough,
sore red eyes, and a widespread blotchy red rash. Dr Donohue said
symptoms usually start around 10 days after contact with an infected
person. "Now is the time for people to be aware of any signs of
infection," Dr Donohue said. "Anyone travelling or living in the
Whitsundays who develops a fever, cough, runny nose and eyes, or a
blotchy red rash in the next few weeks should seek advice from their
GP. However, it's important to call the practice to say they could
have measles, and ask to be seen away from the waiting room to avoid
spreading the disease to others."

--
